                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d351">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760C.62/951: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-08-23T22:00:00+01:00"
                            >August 23, 1939—10 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 23—5:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>325. Immediately upon receipt of the President’s message I called upon Count
                        Ciano<note n="40" xml:id="d351fn40">Galeazzo Ciano di Cortellazza, Italian
                        Minister for Foreign Affairs.</note> and requested an audience with the King
                    who is now near Turin in northern Italy. Ciano consulted with Mussolini over the
                    telephone and subsequently arranged an audience for 2:00 p.m. tomorrow.
                    Consequently I am leaving this evening on the 11:00 o’clock train for Turin.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
